    <p>For this project, I was both the lead UX designer and the lead frontend developer, so I constantly evaluated the feasibility and value of design decisions. A good example of this was a custom Google Calendar module that displays the schedule for group exercise classes. Though proposing this feature would mean custom development work for the dev team, the high priority and significant value it had provided the rationale for spending time on it. In a similar fashion, thatâ€™s how I prioritized modular components, zero-tap facility info, and an entirely-custom WordPress editor interface in the redesigned site, too.</p>


    <p>My biggest design decision on the site was a single page format. Each major program of Rec Sports got one single page containing all necessary content. I supported that with a navigation system so that someone could jump to a specific piece of content via the menu or a URL. Though it was tricky to get this working with WordPress, this balance was the sweet spot between total visibility and a simple, speedy experience.</p>

    <p>After launch, I kept evaluating the success of the site (in fact, that helped us make a key terminology change early on). We also tracked membership signups as a key success metric, and we saw a 19-percent increase immediately following the launch of the site.</p>

